Comment: ‘palm of hand’; Glossed by Lean (Vol. 9:28) as ‘here is the flat object, e.g. bridge’ but I believe this is incorrect. Bridge, which is the same word as ‘corpse’ (or sometimes ‘body’) in many Engan languages, is tó-ko (Lang 1973:131) in E and to-ko in S, which in PE is *tro-nko. However, in S, body is lo-ke.
Name: Enga

Comment: “Twenty is the two hands and both feet bunched together, but there are no words for the separate toes of the left foot. There is no notation, the words are simply the names given to the fingers and toes, starting with the little finger of the right hand and ending with the small toes of the right foot. Twenty is properly a lot of things (see the words ‘many,’ [Everi-ha] also ‘we’ [Hari-everi]).”
Name: Haira

Comment: “However, for twenty-four and following numbers, one can start all over again by adding the word dumon. When doing this it seems that people skip some of the numbers used in the basic system, giving different patterns. Probably out of confusion, because it seemed that they do not use it often. For example, some people I met on a sago grub festival skipped the armpit and/or the middle of the underarm, resulting in nineteen numbers extra to the basic system.”
Name: Kopkaka

Name: Mwakai (Mongol dialect)

Name: Awembiak

Comment: Copied from Anceaux [written at the top of the page]

Comment: it appears that the prefix ni is a verbal particle ... The Prefix ni is in fact a Verbal Particle, and can be applied also to tuwale, tavelima, and saŋavul [<sanavul>, with <n> in italics].
Name: Sugarloaf Island, Mota

Comment: Three is often tolu ... as in counting
Name: Sugarloaf Island, Mota

Comment: four [is often] vati ... as in counting
Name: Sugarloaf Island, Mota

Comment: five is not repeated on the second hand
Name: Sugarloaf Island, Mota

Comment: [<m> in italics, = “nasal”]; The Prefixe tave in tavelima, five, has not been explained, but may be tavaliu, taval lima, hand on one side.
Name: Sugarloaf Island, Mota

Comment: On the second hand lavea, which is prefixed to numerals, is mot reasonably taken as a word signifying the other side, or something above ... tea is a form of the numeral most commonly used for ‘one.’
Name: Sugarloaf Island, Mota

Comment: in lavearua seven, laveatol eight, laveavat nine, the numerals used for two, three, and four, are evidently repeated with a difference ... It is seen at once that the true numerals two, three, four, are rua, tol, vat; which appear again in seven, eight, nine. ... The meaning of the Prefix lavea in the Numerals of the second hand has not been made out ... tea is the Numeral tea, one, obsolete in Mota, but in use elsewhere.
Name: Sugarloaf Island, Mota

Comment: [<sanavul>, with <n> in italics]; but when ten, sanavul, is reached, the word is quite distinct, there is no repetition or recalling of five; and further advance is made by tens, not fives. This, then, is not purely quinary; five is used to get to ten, and then the notation becomes decimal. ... Saŋavul [<sanavul>, with <n> in italics] may be said to be naturally a Substantive.
Name: Sugarloaf Island, Mota

Comment: To mark exactness of reckoning wonowono, full, is used ... full ten
Name: Sugarloaf Island, Mota

Comment: [<sanavul>, with <n> in italics; <m> in italics, = “nasal”]; one ten, the unit above it one
Name: Sugarloaf Island, Mota

Comment: [<m> in italics, = “nasal”]; It is not necessary always to mention the ten
Name: Sugarloaf Island, Mota

Comment: To mark exactness of reckoning wonowono, full, is used ... full twenty
Name: Sugarloaf Island, Mota

Form: saŋavul tol o numei me vat
Comment: [<sanavul>, with <n> in italics; <m> in italics, = “nasal”]; The Verbal particle may equally be me, ti, ta with the numei; ... when past time is declared, ‘three tens the number-above was four.’
Name: Sugarloaf Island, Mota

Comment: and so on up to ninety
Name: Sugarloaf Island, Mota

Comment: [<m> in italics, = “nasal”]; that is, a whole mele leaf.
Name: Sugarloaf Island, Mota

Comment: [<m> in italics, = “nasal”]; o avaviu, from the Verb av to put one thing upon another
Name: Sugarloaf Island, Mota

Comment: [<m> in italics, = “nasal”]; o avaviu, from the Verb av to put one thing upon another
Name: Sugarloaf Island, Mota

Comment: [<sanavul>, with <n> in italics]; hundred once, and the pile above ten
Name: Sugarloaf Island, Mota

Form: melnol vagarua o avaviu sanavul tavelima
Comment: [both <m>s in italics, = “nasal”; <sanavul>, with <n> in italics]; twice hundred, the sum-above-hundred five tens.
Name: Sugarloaf Island, Mota

Comment: Substantive, Adjective, or Verb ... The exact use of tar for a thousand is settled in native usage as ten hundreds, but the word is also loosely used for any great number. There is no name for a sum greater than a thousand
Name: Sugarloaf Island, Mota

Form: tar vatuwale, melnol laveatol, o avaviu saŋavul laveatol, o numei nivat
Comment: [all <m>s in italics, = “nasal”; <sanavul>, with <n> in italics]; thousand once, hundreds eight, the sum-above-hundreds eight tens, the unit-above four.
Name: Sugarloaf Island, Mota

Form: tar vatuwale, melnol vagalaveatol, o avaviu saŋavul laveatol, o numei nivat
Comment: [all <m>s in italics, = “nasal”; <sanavul>, with <n> in italics]; thousand once, hundreds eight times, the sum-above-hundreds eight tens, the unit-above four.
Name: Sugarloaf Island, Mota

Comment: These numerals are all different from any that I can discover elsewhere they appear to be entirely indigenous, and not in use even in the island nearest to Mota. We have, therefore, the phenomenon of a people inventing a series of numerals for themselves which is decimal, and using it in a game, while they continue to use for ordinary purposes their old notation, the basis of which is quinary. ... sa, though never used as one in Mota, is in fact the same as tea, which appears in the Mota word for six and qasa 1, the first qa, corresponds to qaru 6, the second qa ... It is very remarkable that in counting in the game of tika, and in that only, a regular decimal series of Numerals is in use ... These Numerals appear to be peculiar to Mota, and of native invention, none of them corresponding to the Numerals of other islands.
Name: Mota (purely decimal series of numerals used in a game)

Comment: Of the words, wura, two, may be the same as that used in Dual Imperative
Name: Mota (purely decimal series of numerals used in a game)

Comment: From Kienzle and Campbell: “Counting is done using te [sic] right hand as a pointer and starting with the fingers on the left hand, the fingers of which are folded up in turn, commencing with the little finger. They then work up the left arm touching the salient points such as wrist, forearm, elbow, bicep, shoulder, neck, ear, eye and bridge of the nose. The same procedure is then continued in reverse order down the right side using the left hand to touch the parts mentioned.”
Name: Telifomin

Comment: appears to consist of a reduplicated monosyllabic form. This could be in origin iconic
Name: Ulwa (Manu dialect)

Comment: appears to contain reduplication. Of course, there is less logical justification for calling this iconic, but perhaps the form was derived by analogy from the preceding form in the series of numerals
Name: Ulwa (Manu dialect)

Comment: watangïn ‘last bunch (of bananas) to emerge’ + ila ‘morota frond’. The word watangïn seems to be used in a more general sense to refer to the last of a series (it also refers to the ‘pinky finger’, for example). In traditional timekeeping, days can be marked by the breaking of one ila ‘morota frond’ each day. The word watangïnila ‘four’, thus seems to mean something like ‘the last straw’.
Name: Ulwa (Manu dialect)

Comment: transparently derived from anga ‘piece, side’ plus i ‘hand, arm’
Name: Ulwa (Manu dialect)

Comment: ‘one side of hand (= five); (someone) cut one and put (it) on top of them’ (= six)

Name: Ulwa (Manu dialect)

Comment: ‘one side of hand (= five); (someone) cut four and put (them) on top of them’ (= nine)

Comment: An alternate form, nali ‘ten’, reflects the traditional system for counting larger numbers in Ulwa, as this word also refers to the spines of sago fronds, which were used to mark units of ten when counting larger sums.
Name: Ulwa (Manu dialect)

Comment: ‘pig(’s) head’, a term reflecting modern Papua New Guinean currency, as the twenty-kina note has the picture of a pig’s head
Name: Ulwa (Manu dialect)

Comment: ‘person(’s) head’, this phrase likewise reflecting the fact that the fifty-kina note contains the image of a man’s head (that of Prime Minister Michael Somare).
Name: Ulwa (Manu dialect)

Comment: ‘(one) bird’, similarly derived from the fact that the hundred-kina note contains the image of a bird (a bird-of-paradise, the nation’s symbol)
Name: Ulwa (Manu dialect)
